6","1166":"1166","1066":"1066","about 1066":"about 1066","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert d'Arbetot was born about 1066, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Unknown before 1090, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died before 1166."},"et":{"about 1066–before 1166":"umbes 1066–enne 1166","–Female":"Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1066–1166":"1066–1166","before 1090":"enne 1090","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090","before 1166":"enne 1166","1166":"1166","1066":"1066","about 1066":"umbes 1066","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1066–before 1166":"noin 1066–ennen vuotta 1166","–Female":"Kuollut","1090–Female":"1090–Kuollut","1066–1166":"1066–1166","before 1090":"ennen vuotta 1090"